        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Can we make a definition of `cython.const`  such that mypy (and similar) are happy for code like\r\n\r\n```\r\na: cython.const[cython.int] = 1\r\n```\r\n\r\nsince I think what a lot of people want is to write type annotations that Cython can use but which also pass their static type checkers.\r\n\r\n(We've already missed here with our typed memoryview syntax though, but maybe it'd be good to make sure future additions meet this.)\r\n\r\nI'm definitely not an expert in the Python-typing ecosystem though, and I remain generally suspicious of it. So I really can't make an informed comment on whether either `const[int]` or `int[const]` meets that criteria. I suspect `Annotated[int, const]` does, but I agree with all the other criticism of it.",
